Patch Set 7:

> Patch Set 7:
> 
> Rather than having a blanket "subnm_raise_privs" flag, would it make more sense to make this fine-grained, so that this is a mask of *which* privileges can be raised?

So maybe one sub_nm_xx role for each of the 5 properties we have identified?
- the 'admin' property, defining whether root is squashed;
- the 'trusted' property, permitting to see the file system's
  canonical identifiers;
- the 'deny_unknown' property, denying all access to users not
  explicitly mapped;
- the 'readonly_mount' property, forcing clients to read-only mount;
- the 'rbac' property, defining admin roles.

Patch Set 7:

I was looking at struct nodemap_cluster_roles_rec for the RBAC roles, and it looks like there is lots of space available for adding in the "raise roles" flags.  What I would suggest is to use ncrr_unused1 for the "raise roles" flags, so they can both use the same enum values:

 struct nodemap_cluster_roles_rec {
        enum nodemap_rbac_roles ncrr_roles:64;                               
        enum nodemap_rbac_roles ncrr_roles_raise:64;                           
        __u64                   ncrr_unused2;                                   
        __u64                   ncrr_unused3;                                 
 };

It might also make sense to use ncrr_unused2 or unused3 for the per-nodemask Linux capabilities flags (LU-17410), and whether sub-nodemaps can raise these flags?
